For in order to give validity to such acts, there is required the consent of the People, either by itself, or by those who legitimately represent the People3 as may bc understood by what we have said above respect·- ing alienation. By the application of these distinctions, it will be easy to judge whether the pleas of kings who refuse to pay their predecessors’ debts, not being their heirs, are just or unjust: of which examples may be seen in Bodinus.

XIII. Nor is that which many have delivered, that the favours of Princes, granted out of pure liberality, may at any time be rer voked, to be allowed to pass on without distinction. For there are some grants which the king makes out of his own property, and which, except they are granted expressly during pleasure only, have the force of a complete donation. And these cannot be revoked, except, in the case of subjects, in the way of penalty, or for the sake of public utility, and then with compensation if it may be. There are other grants which merely remove legal restrictions without any contraet. These are revocable. Because, as the law which is re- laxed universally may always be re—established universally, so, that which is relaxed particularly may be re-established particularly. For in this case no right against the author of the law is acquired.
